# Splitting code

## When to split

- **Single responsibility**: a file or function does more than one clear job (e.g. HTTP shaping + DB + rules).
- **Size & scanability**: very long functions or files that are hard to review or test; extract named units with stable inputs/outputs.
- **Reuse**: the same block appears twice; extract once to `utils/` or a small helper in the same layer, not copy-paste.
- **Testing**: logic is hard to unit-test because it is tangled with I/O; pull pure/orchestration pieces into **services** or focused helpers.

## Where pieces go (layering)

- **Routes**: stay thin; split only for route groups or versioning, not for business logic.
- **Controllers**: split by resource or by clear HTTP concerns; never move DB or domain rules here.
- **Services**: split orchestration and domain rules into cohesive modules; one “area” per file when it grows.
- **Repos**: split by aggregate/table or query family; keep Express out of repos.
- **Utils**: small, stateless helpers; avoid a catch-all — if it grows domain meaning, promote to service/repo.

## When not to split

- **Speculation**: do not carve abstractions “for later”; split when duplication or complexity is real.
- **Tiny indirection**: avoid one-line wrappers or files that only re-export unless they stabilize a public API boundary.
- **PR scope**: prefer splitting **work** into small PRs (see project `split-to-prs` guidance when applicable), not scattering one feature across many files without need.

## Checks before finishing a split

- Imports respect direction: **routes → controllers → services → repos** (no upward or sideways leakage of HTTP into data layer).
- New files have one primary purpose; names match what callers expect.
- Behavior covered by existing tests updated or a short manual/ automated test plan.
